</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F07EC5B90AACC29D555EF7ADE31BEB96" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="54DD445E354B546B20216F9A67C0CE70" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="887A1D5397E795A3802CFE987356DCD6" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">
<taxonomicName id="3B56013A1793446BAC56F23F0C0E648C" authorityName="Schwarzhans" authorityYear="2013" class="Actinopterygii" family="Myctophidae" genus="Diogenichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Diogenichthys aguilerai" order="Myctophiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="aguilerai">
<emphasis id="904EA680D11846EE69FD44E4BD175C9F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Diogenichthys aguilerai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is an unspectacular and small high-bodied myctophid otolith with a ratio OL:OH of 0.95-1.05. Its ventral rim is regularly curved and smooth; the dorsal rim is highest slightly behind its middle. Rostrum, excisura, and antirostrum are all small. The inner face is flat, and the outer face is distinctly convex and smooth. The narrow sulcus exhibits a slightly longer ostium than cauda, with the latter being underlain by a very long, anteriorly extended pseudocolliculum.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F404B18B9B447B5A698C1C2689E7A1D6" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">
<taxonomicName id="E333EE4F06A481A586DD8B6996F0C355" authorityName="Schwarzhans" authorityYear="2013" class="Actinopterygii" family="Myctophidae" genus="Diogenichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Diogenichthys aguilerai" order="Myctophiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="aguilerai">
<emphasis id="40029F72988D1F5D72601C1B4268AE3E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Diogenichthys aguilerai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was apparently widespread during the early Miocene (Aquitanian and Burdigalian) but usually not common, with the exception of a recent find in the late Burdigalian of Chile (
<bibRefCitation id="37F0DB598AB5C8878B0CD4941E1D7A66" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1186/s13358-021-00228-w" author="Schwarzhans, WW" journalOrPublisher="Paleobiology" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" refId="B63" refString="Schwarzhans, WW, Nielsen, SN, 2021. Fish otoliths from the early Miocene of Chile: a window into the evolution of marine bony fishes in the Southeast Pacific. Swiss Journal of Palaeontology 140: e16. [62 pp] https://doi.org/10.1186/s13358-021-00228-w" title="Fish otoliths from the early Miocene of Chile: a window into the evolution of marine bony fishes in the Southeast Pacific. Swiss Journal of Palaeontology 140: e 16. [62 pp]" url="https://doi.org/10.1186/s13358-021-00228-w" year="2021">Schwarzhans and Nielsen 2021</bibRefCitation>
). It was originally described from Angola (
<bibRefCitation id="C64CE604FF9F189161826B6902FDE494" author="Schwarzhans, W" journalOrPublisher="Palaeo Ichthyologica" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" pagination="151 - 184" refId="B59" refString="Schwarzhans, W, 2013b. Otoliths from the Miocene of West Africa, primarily from the Mandorove Formation of Gabon. Palaeo Ichthyologica 13: 151 - 184" title="Otoliths from the Miocene of West Africa, primarily from the Mandorove Formation of Gabon." volume="13" year="2013 b">Schwarzhans 2013b</bibRefCitation>
) but is also known from New Zealand (
<bibRefCitation id="EAA320382A8E86A07EDB880FC1AC1489" author="Schwarzhans, W" journalOrPublisher="Memorie Della Societa Italiana Di Scienze Naturali e Del Museon Di Storia Naturale Di Milano" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" pagination="3 - 326" refId="B60" refString="Schwarzhans, W, 2019. Reconstruction of the fossil marine bony fish fauna (Teleostei) from the Eocene to Pleistocene of New Zealand by means of otoliths. Memorie Della Societa Italiana Di Scienze Naturali e Del Museon Di Storia Naturale Di Milano 46: 3 - 326" title="Reconstruction of the fossil marine bony fish fauna (Teleostei) from the Eocene to Pleistocene of New Zealand by means of otoliths." volume="46" year="2019">Schwarzhans 2019</bibRefCitation>
) and possibly also from the Caribbean (as 
<taxonomicName id="6CEF2474FFF83D2D0D28B58D138F7B8A" class="Actinopterygii" family="Myctophidae" genus="Diogenichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Diogenichthys" order="Myctophiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="223EE764F0FE001D4954CD33855C8EFE" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Diogenichthys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. in 
<bibRefCitation id="4748809BF0BD9518DEA8C530CAB7CF1D" author="Schwarzhans, W" journalOrPublisher="Palaeo Ichthyologica" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" pagination="83 - 150" refId="B61" refString="Schwarzhans, W, Aguilera, OA, 2013. Otoliths of the Myctophidae from the Neogene of tropical America. Palaeo Ichthyologica 13: 83 - 150" title="Otoliths of the Myctophidae from the Neogene of tropical America." volume="13" year="2013">Schwarzhans and Aguilera 2013</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
